payload_pull_request_body: I know that mediawiki is not such a popular format to export to and import from, but I wanted to create a new plugin in order to have a better understanding of the whole import process and I figured that some use cases may actually exist. For example, if somebody wants to import a table from: - wikipedia; - redmine; - other crm wikis or any other mediawiki pages; - exported mediawiki file from phpMyAdmin (which may now act as a backup the user exported before altering some tables). I've listed here some implementation details: - Before importing, the user can select the import type: - Memory saving (will import one table at a time). Recommended for a large number of tables. - Faster, but memory consuming (will save all tables into memory). Recommended for small amounts of data. - A new default configuration setting is added to provide the above mentioned functionality: $cfg['Import']['mediawiki_performance_indicator'] = 'memory'; The other value it can take is 'speed'. - Provides parsing of the mediawiki format for tables as seen at [0] and treats special cases such as split lines when reading chunk by chunk; - Table names are imported from comments, otherwise generic names are given: TABLE 1, TABLE 2, etc; - If the table headers are empty, the columns will be imported as COL 1, COL 2, etc; - More details in the comments. I hope this will be useful for someone, Alex [0] http://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/Help:Tables

Created class to manage OpenGL textures, fixed alpha testing Created the Texture object to encapsulate an OpenGL texture. This object is more in line with RAII, since it creates a texture on construction and deletes it on destruction. Later on, when we start using C++11, we can wrap this in a shared pointer and make some of our image resources more exception-safe, something I haven't been paying nearly enough attention to unfortunately. While doing this, I stepped through the texture creation code and discovered an issue. We blit image textures to an RGBA surface in order to convert all images to RGBA before sending them to the GPU. But this blotting process is dropping the alpha channel for some reason. Instead of this approach, we will determine the format of the image and send that to the GPU without an intermediary surface. After this, alpha testing for sprites started working again. No more black boxes around the characters! :D
